args: Deep in the Lodyzhka Mountains that\nseparate North and South Grastaea...
Whoa! Never seen a bird like that up north.
We are not here for birdwatching,\nJoachim.
What's the harm in taking in the sights?\nCall it ＂recon.＂ This place is full of things\nwe'd never see back home.
True. The land grows greener the further\nsouth we travel.
If our homeland enjoyed this same bounty\nof nature, we would have no need for war.
Whoa there, Commander, no need to\nwax philosophical. Just kick back and\nenjoy the birds' song, all right?
Where did that log come from?!
We just walked into a trap—and a familiar\none at that. It couldn't be...
I must admit, I did not expect to see\nyou here.
It has been some time, Kirsty. Or should\nI address you as Commander now?
I would prefer you didn't address me at all,\nFORMER Commander.
I see. I take it you're irritated I chose to\nignore my return orders?
No, that came as no surprise.\nYou were never one for rules.
But disobeying a direct order is a violation\nof military law. I should have your head\nfor that alone.
Easy, Commander. No need for that.
He tried to kill us just moments ago,\nJoachim!
Come on, I bet he was just trying to\nscare us. Right, Victor?

I'm afraid I had every intention to kill.
I caught word that envoys to the empire
would be passing through here, so I
set a trap.

If our war hawk of a homeland and the
barbaric Dyrenell Empire were to join
forces, the continent would be riddled
with death and destruction.
Don't let personal vendettas cloud your\njudgment, Victor. I know about your\nhistory with them.
I expected no less. But do you truly believe\nan alliance would be in anyone's best\ninterests?
Our nation is still weak. With the support\nof the Empire, expanding our reach would\nbe much simpler.
It would mean longer lives for our\ncomrades.
Your words are naught but petty idealism.
Don't speak like you know what's best\nfor our country. While you idled here,\nour comrades were dying for our nation!
＂For our nation＂? You know as well as I\nthat those wars are in the interest of\nthe wealthy minority.
Our homeland has been rotten since our\nformer king's passing.
So that's why abandoned Svenitla, is it?\nAnd now you impede this alliance to spite\nthe king who demoted you.
No. I simply found something I cared\nabout here.
And any who threaten that will face\nthe whole of my wrath—even my\nformer comrades.
A soldier's duty is to their nation,\nnot their emotions.
Don't let him get to you, Commander.
...Victor. As a former comrade,\nlet me give you a warning.
If you impede us again, we will show\nno mercy.
Why wait? Show me how your\ntraining has progressed.
Easy, you two!\nPut away your weapons!
Stay out of this, Joachim. He won't back\ndown. He's been that way since he was\nmy instructor.

I may be unchanged, but the same cannot
be said of you. You follow orders without
pause, despite knowing how corrupt our
nation's leaders are.
I had thought ten years enough for you\nto see clearly again, but it appears I\nwas mistaken.
And I taught you better than to leave\nyourself open! HAH!
Heh... Just made it.\nAre you hurt?
Saved by your subordinate, eh? You may\nlack in moral fortitude, but you seem to\nat least be worthy of admiration.
Give the insults a rest, Victor.
If you don't, I might have to kill\nyou myself.
Hah! Stow your fears, boy. I have no\ninterest in pursuing this further.\nYou are free to journey on.
If my words alone can unsettle her,\nshe is no threat to me.

I have told you time and time again that
an army represents power, not justice.
One can only find justice within their
own heart.
So long as you ignore your own emotions,\nyou will never achieve anything.
Even after you were demoted, you still\nobeyed any orders you were given.
What did you find in the south to change\nyou like this? What happened?
...I just met some interesting people.\nThat's all.
